1
00:00:00,080 --> 00:00:04,160
Traders today are bombarded 
with "smart money concepts",  

2
00:00:04,160 --> 00:00:11,240
claiming to reveal the secrets of big players.
But these ideas aren't as new as you might think!
  

3
00:00:11,240 --> 00:00:16,000
These concepts are just a modern 
remix of the Wyckoff method. 

4
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:21,000
The Wyckoff method, developed nearly a 
century ago, is the original blueprint  

5
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:26,400
for understanding smart money trading! 
 
This is the video you need to watch,  

6
00:00:26,400 --> 00:00:31,731
if you really want to learn about the 
inception of smart money concepts!
  

7
00:00:31,731 --> 00:00:34,040
Understanding Market Dynamics
Trading isn't a fair game. It's  

8
00:00:34,040 --> 00:00:40,520
not you against other small traders. It's 
you against big players with deep pockets. 

9
00:00:40,520 --> 00:00:46,920
These big traders have more money, better 
tools, and access to info you don't have. 
  

10
00:00:46,920 --> 00:00:53,840
They know how retail traders think. And they 
use this to trick small traders like you and me. 

11
00:00:53,840 --> 00:00:57,560
Here’s the reality: the 
odds aren't in your favor!
  

12
00:00:57,560 --> 00:01:01,880
Wyckoff teaches you to use 
logic to figure out the market. 

13
00:01:01,880 --> 00:01:08,120
The big idea is this: when smart money buy 
or sell, they leave marks on charts. These  

14
00:01:08,120 --> 00:01:13,400
marks show up in price and volume data.
 
If you know how to read these signs,  

15
00:01:13,400 --> 00:01:19,320
you can trade along with the pros. You're 
not their prey anymore. You're on their side. 

16
00:01:19,320 --> 00:01:23,360
And you're not just guessing 
anymore. You have a map.
  

17
00:01:23,360 --> 00:01:24,960
The Three Fundamental Laws
The Wyckoff method is built  

18
00:01:24,960 --> 00:01:31,080
on three key laws that explain how markets 
work. These laws help you see what's really  

19
00:01:31,080 --> 00:01:38,160
moving prices, not just what's on the surface.
Let's start with the Law of Supply and Demand. 

20
00:01:38,160 --> 00:01:44,000
This law is the engine that drives the market. 
 
It's pretty simple: when more people  

21
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:51,320
want to buy than sell, prices go up.
When more want to sell than buy, prices go down. 

22
00:01:51,320 --> 00:01:55,240
But it's not just about 
numbers of buyers and sellers. 

23
00:01:55,240 --> 00:01:58,280
It's about how much money 
they're willing to spend. 

24
00:01:58,280 --> 00:02:03,280
It's about the intensity of their actions.
One big buyer can have more  

25
00:02:03,280 --> 00:02:09,080
impact than many small sellers.
 
The Law of Supply and Demand says that price,  

26
00:02:09,080 --> 00:02:14,280
volume, and trend, all work together.
Price shows which way the market is  

27
00:02:14,280 --> 00:02:21,480
going. Volume shows how strong that move is.
When price and volume agree, it confirms the  

28
00:02:21,480 --> 00:02:28,000
market direction. We’ll talk about this later.
 
The Law of Cause and Effect tells us that big  

29
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:33,800
moves in the market don't just happen out 
of nowhere. They need preparation. It's  

30
00:02:33,800 --> 00:02:39,320
like a rocket launch. Before a rocket 
can take off, it needs a lot of fuel. 

31
00:02:39,320 --> 00:02:45,560
In the market, that fuel is buying or 
selling pressure building up over time.
  

32
00:02:45,560 --> 00:02:49,160
The size of the cause determines 
the size of the effect. 

33
00:02:49,160 --> 00:02:55,440
A small cause leads to a small move.
A big cause can lead to a big move. 

34
00:02:55,440 --> 00:03:00,600
This is why Wyckoff traders look for 
signs of accumulation (which is buying)  

35
00:03:00,600 --> 00:03:07,480
or distribution (meaning, selling). These are 
the "causes" that can lead to big price moves.
  

36
00:03:07,480 --> 00:03:12,720
This law helps explain why markets 
sometimes seem to move for no reason. 

37
00:03:12,720 --> 00:03:18,560
There's always a reason, but it might have been 
building up for a while, before you noticed it.
  

38
00:03:18,560 --> 00:03:24,880
The Law of Cause and Effect also says that if 
there's no preparation, there will be no move. 

39
00:03:24,880 --> 00:03:29,880
This helps you avoid false signals. 
If you don't see a cause building up,  

40
00:03:29,880 --> 00:03:35,320
you shouldn't expect a big effect.
 
It’s all about preparation. In the market,  

41
00:03:35,320 --> 00:03:41,760
this often shows up as trading ranges. These 
are periods where price moves sideways,  

42
00:03:41,760 --> 00:03:48,800
bouncing between support and resistance levels.
To the untrained eye, these might look boring.  

43
00:03:48,800 --> 00:03:53,080
But to a Wyckoff trader, they're 
exciting. They're where the cause  

44
00:03:53,080 --> 00:03:59,720
is building up for the next big move. 
 
 
Lastly, we have the Law of Effort versus Result.  

45
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:04,160
This law helps us spot when 
something's off in the market. 

46
00:04:04,160 --> 00:04:11,400
It's about comparing the effort (usually measured 
by volume) with the result (the price movement).
  

47
00:04:11,400 --> 00:04:17,120
Here's how it works. The market is always 
trying to move one way or the other. 

48
00:04:17,120 --> 00:04:24,800
These attempts can be short or long. Either way, 
they represent effort, which we see as volume. 

49
00:04:24,800 --> 00:04:31,120
If you see a lot of volume (meaning effort) 
but prices barely move (meaning result),  

50
00:04:31,120 --> 00:04:33,760
that's a red flag.
It might mean the  

51
00:04:33,760 --> 00:04:39,960
current trend is running out of steam. 
 
On the flip side, if prices move a lot on  

52
00:04:39,960 --> 00:04:46,880
low volume, that move might not last.
This law helps you spot divergences. 

53
00:04:46,880 --> 00:04:52,760
A divergence is when the effort and result 
don't match up. It's like a warning sign that  

54
00:04:52,760 --> 00:04:57,600
something might be about to change.
 
The Law of Effort versus Result is  

55
00:04:57,600 --> 00:05:03,760
like a lie detector for the market, and is 
especially useful for spotting trend changes. 

56
00:05:03,760 --> 00:05:09,600
Often, before a trend changes, you'll 
see a mismatch between effort and result. 

57
00:05:09,600 --> 00:05:14,200
It's like the market is trying hard 
to keep going in the same direction,  

58
00:05:14,200 --> 00:05:16,960
but it's running out of steam.
 
Wyckoff Phases 

59
00:05:16,960 --> 00:05:21,400
The Wyckoff method breaks down 
market action into four main phases:  

60
00:05:21,400 --> 00:05:29,800
Accumulation… Mark-up…Distribution…and Mark-down.
 
Accumulation is the first phase. It happens at  

61
00:05:29,800 --> 00:05:35,480
market bottoms. This is when big players 
start buying. They do this quietly,  

62
00:05:35,480 --> 00:05:40,120
so prices don't go up too fast.
During this phase, prices often  

63
00:05:40,120 --> 00:05:46,040
move sideways. It might look boring, but 
a lot is happening under the surface.
  

64
00:05:46,040 --> 00:05:52,280
In accumulation, most people are scared to 
buy. They think prices might keep falling. 

65
00:05:52,280 --> 00:05:57,000
But smart money sees value. 
They buy when others are afraid. 

66
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:02,680
This phase can last a while. It takes 
time for big players to buy all they want,  

67
00:06:02,680 --> 00:06:06,520
without pushing prices up too much.
 
Look for these signs: 

68
00:06:06,520 --> 00:06:14,860
• Prices stop falling and move sideways
• Volume is low, but picks up on price dips 

69
00:06:14,860 --> 00:06:21,560
• Price drops don't last long
• Strong buying when prices fall a bit
  

70
00:06:21,560 --> 00:06:27,320
The uptrend or mark-up phase comes next. 
This is when prices start to climb. 

71
00:06:27,320 --> 00:06:32,680
The big players who bought during 
accumulation are now letting prices rise. 

72
00:06:32,680 --> 00:06:37,240
They might even buy more, pushing prices higher.
In the uptrend,  

73
00:06:37,240 --> 00:06:43,360
more people start to notice the market.
They see prices going up and want to join in.  

74
00:06:43,360 --> 00:06:49,400
This extra buying helps push prices even higher. 
 
Look for these signs in an uptrend: 

75
00:06:49,400 --> 00:06:56,440
• Prices make higher highs and higher lows
• Volume often increases as prices rise 

76
00:06:56,440 --> 00:07:03,280
• Pullbacks are short and shallow
• Each new high is met with strong buying
  

77
00:07:03,280 --> 00:07:08,120
The third phase is distribution. 
This happens at market tops. 

78
00:07:08,120 --> 00:07:14,920
Big players who bought low are now selling.
They sell slowly, just like they bought slowly. 

79
00:07:14,920 --> 00:07:18,360
They don't want to crash the 
market by selling too fast.
  

80
00:07:18,360 --> 00:07:25,120
In distribution, most people are excited. 
They think prices will keep going up forever. 

81
00:07:25,120 --> 00:07:30,901
But smart money knows better. They're 
quietly selling to these eager buyers. 

82
00:07:30,901 --> 00:07:33,680
Like accumulation, distribution 
can take some time.
  

83
00:07:33,680 --> 00:07:38,980
Look for these signs in distribution:
• Prices stop rising and move sideways 

84
00:07:38,980 --> 00:07:43,480
• Volume might increase, 
but price rises don't last 

85
00:07:43,480 --> 00:07:51,480
• More volatility, with sharp ups and downs
• Each new high is quickly sold into
  

86
00:07:51,480 --> 00:07:57,640
The last phase is the downtrend or 
mark-down. This is when prices start to fall. 

87
00:07:57,640 --> 00:08:03,680
The big players have finished selling. Now 
there aren't enough buyers to keep prices up. 

88
00:08:03,680 --> 00:08:10,520
In the downtrend, fear takes over. People 
who bought high start to panic and sell. 

89
00:08:10,520 --> 00:08:17,640
This pushes prices down even faster. Like the 
uptrend, the downtrend often moves in waves. 
  

90
00:08:18,200 --> 00:08:23,520
Look for these signs in a downtrend:
• Prices make lower lows and lower highs 

91
00:08:23,520 --> 00:08:29,440
• Volume often increases as prices fall
• Bounces are short and weak 

92
00:08:29,440 --> 00:08:36,960
• Each new low is met with more selling
 
These phases don't always happen in a perfect  

93
00:08:36,960 --> 00:08:44,520
cycle. Markets are messy. Sometimes a phase 
might be skipped, or cut short. Other times,  

94
00:08:44,520 --> 00:08:50,200
a phase might last longer than expected.
The key is to be flexible, and watch  

95
00:08:50,200 --> 00:08:54,440
for the signs of each phase.
 
In accumulation, you start to  

96
00:08:54,440 --> 00:08:59,800
get ready to buy. You look for signs 
that big players are accumulating.  

97
00:08:59,800 --> 00:09:07,040
These signs might include failed attempts to push 
prices lower, or strong buying when prices dip. 

98
00:09:07,040 --> 00:09:13,440
During the uptrend, the goal is to buy pullbacks. 
These are temporary dips in an overall rising  

99
00:09:13,440 --> 00:09:20,280
market. You wait for the uptrend to be confirmed 
before buying. You don't try to guess the bottom. 

100
00:09:20,280 --> 00:09:26,800
In distribution, you start to get cautious. You 
might take profits on long positions. You watch  

101
00:09:26,800 --> 00:09:32,600
for signs that the uptrend is weakening. These 
signs could include failed attempts to make  

102
00:09:32,600 --> 00:09:40,560
new highs, or increased selling at high prices.
During the downtrend, the goal is to sell short. 
  

103
00:09:40,560 --> 00:09:47,760
Most of the money in a trend is made in phase 
2 (the uptrend) and phase 4 (the downtrend). 

104
00:09:47,760 --> 00:09:53,680
The transition phases (accumulation and 
distribution) are often trickier to trade.  

105
00:09:53,680 --> 00:09:59,320
They're more about preparing for the next trend.
One key skill in using the Wyckoff method  

106
00:09:59,840 --> 00:10:03,880
is identifying changes in market 
character. This is when the  

107
00:10:03,880 --> 00:10:09,800
market shifts from one phase to another. 
 
For example, the shift from accumulation to  

108
00:10:09,800 --> 00:10:16,240
uptrend, or from distribution to downtrend.
These changes often happen gradually. The  

109
00:10:16,240 --> 00:10:22,800
market doesn't suddenly switch from one phase 
to another. Instead, it transitions slowly. 
  

110
00:10:22,800 --> 00:10:29,600
Another important aspect of the Wyckoff method, is 
understanding the concept of supply and demand. In  

111
00:10:29,600 --> 00:10:36,440
accumulation, demand is slowly overcoming supply.
In distribution, supply is slowly overcoming  

112
00:10:36,440 --> 00:10:41,480
demand. The uptrend and downtrend 
are when these forces play out.
  

113
00:10:41,480 --> 00:10:47,760
Volume plays a crucial role in identifying 
these phases. In accumulation, volume often  

114
00:10:47,760 --> 00:10:51,480
increases on price dips.
In distribution,  

115
00:10:51,480 --> 00:10:57,600
volume often increases on price rises. 
 
Another key point: in both accumulation  

116
00:10:57,600 --> 00:11:02,760
and distribution, big players are 
trying to hide what they're doing. 

117
00:11:02,760 --> 00:11:07,880
They don't want everyone to know they're 
buying or selling big amounts. That’s because  

118
00:11:07,880 --> 00:11:13,480
they would move prices before they're ready.
 
This is where the idea of "smart money" comes  

119
00:11:13,480 --> 00:11:19,320
in. These are the big, well-informed players.
And they're always trying to stay ahead  

120
00:11:19,320 --> 00:11:24,120
of the "uninformed" traders.
Remember this: accumulation and  

121
00:11:24,120 --> 00:11:30,640
distribution are about more than just buying and 
selling. They're about the transfer of risk. 
  

122
00:11:30,640 --> 00:11:37,200
In accumulation, smart money is taking on 
risk, betting that prices will go up. In  

123
00:11:37,200 --> 00:11:42,760
distribution, they're passing that risk 
to others, to less informed traders.
  

124
00:11:42,760 --> 00:11:49,480
And one more thing to remember: emotions play 
a big role in these cycles. In accumulation,  

125
00:11:49,480 --> 00:11:55,400
fear is the main emotion. People are scared 
to buy because prices have been falling. 

126
00:11:55,400 --> 00:11:59,240
In distribution, it's often 
greed and fear of missing out. 

127
00:11:59,760 --> 00:12:04,360
People buy because they're afraid 
of missing the next big move up. 

128
00:12:04,360 --> 00:12:10,040
Now, before we continue, let us know in the 
comments what topics you’d like us to cover!  

129
00:12:10,040 --> 00:12:13,320
Tell us what you want to watch next!
 
 
Wyckoff Events

130
00:12:13,320 --> 00:12:18,040
Now let's break down Wyckoff events. 
They're like clues that help us figure  

131
00:12:18,040 --> 00:12:23,800
out what's really going on in the market.
First, we have the Preliminary Support.  

132
00:12:23,800 --> 00:12:29,160
This is when big players start to buy, 
trying to stop prices from falling more. 

133
00:12:29,680 --> 00:12:35,440
It's like putting a floor under the market. 
You might see prices stop dropping as fast,  

134
00:12:35,440 --> 00:12:38,760
or even bounce a little.
Next comes the Selling  

135
00:12:38,760 --> 00:12:44,800
Climax. This is a big moment. It's when 
scared sellers dump their positions. 

136
00:12:44,800 --> 00:12:51,400
Prices often fall hard and fast. But the 
big players are buying during this panic.  

137
00:12:51,400 --> 00:12:57,520
They're getting ready for prices to go up later.
After the Selling Climax, we see an Automatic  

138
00:12:57,520 --> 00:13:02,200
Rally. Prices bounce up a bit.
This happens because the selling  

139
00:13:02,200 --> 00:13:05,240
pressure eases off.
It's like the market  

140
00:13:05,240 --> 00:13:11,240
taking a breath after all that selling.
Then we have the Secondary Test. Prices  

141
00:13:11,240 --> 00:13:16,680
fall again, but not as low as before.
This is important. It shows that  

142
00:13:16,680 --> 00:13:21,320
the big drop might be over.
Big players are still buying,  

143
00:13:21,320 --> 00:13:26,480
keeping prices from falling too far.
Now we come to the Spring. This is a  

144
00:13:26,480 --> 00:13:32,520
tricky move. Prices dip below the low point of 
the Secondary Test. It looks like the market  

145
00:13:32,520 --> 00:13:39,000
might fall more. But it's often a fake-out.
Prices quickly jump back up. This is a key  

146
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:44,560
sign that big players are done buying 
and are ready for prices to go up. 

147
00:13:44,560 --> 00:13:51,520
After the Spring, we see a Sign of Strength. This 
is a strong move up, often with lots of trading. 

148
00:13:51,520 --> 00:13:55,240
It's like the market saying, 
"We're ready to go up now." 

149
00:13:55,240 --> 00:14:02,360
And then we have the Last Point of Support. This 
is one more dip before the real uptrend starts. 

150
00:14:02,360 --> 00:14:06,840
It's like the market taking one 
last breath before climbing.
  

151
00:14:06,840 --> 00:14:12,040
These events don't always happen in 
this exact order. Markets are tricky  

152
00:14:12,040 --> 00:14:17,440
and always changing. But knowing these 
events helps you see the big picture. 

153
00:14:17,440 --> 00:14:22,280
If you see signs of accumulation (like 
the Preliminary Support or Spring),  

154
00:14:22,280 --> 00:14:28,720
it might be a good time to think about buying.
If you see signs of distribution (like a Buying  

155
00:14:28,720 --> 00:14:35,600
Climax or Sign of Weakness), it might be time 
to be careful or even think about selling. 

156
00:14:35,600 --> 00:14:42,400
The end of an accumulation phase, like after a 
successful Spring, can be a great time to buy. 

157
00:14:42,400 --> 00:14:46,960
The end of a distribution phase 
can be a good time to sell.
  

158
00:14:46,960 --> 00:14:51,240
But remember, you don't need to 
catch the exact bottom or top.  

159
00:14:51,240 --> 00:14:56,720
What matters is catching the main move.
And don't get too hung up on naming each  

160
00:14:56,720 --> 00:15:02,400
event. What's more important is understanding 
what these events mean. They're showing you  

161
00:15:02,400 --> 00:15:07,720
the transfer of risk in the market.
Like I said before, in accumulation,  

162
00:15:07,720 --> 00:15:13,360
smart money is taking on risk, betting 
prices will go up. In distribution,  

163
00:15:13,360 --> 00:15:17,193
they're passing that risk to others.
 
 
Volume Analysis in Wyckoff Method 

164
00:15:17,193 --> 00:15:22,760
Volume is a key part of the Wyckoff method. 
It helps confirm what price is telling us. 

165
00:15:22,760 --> 00:15:27,200
The main idea is simple: volume 
should match price moves. 

166
00:15:27,200 --> 00:15:33,800
If prices go up, volume should too. 
If prices fall, volume should rise. 

167
00:15:33,800 --> 00:15:37,800
When volume and price don't 
match, it can mean trouble .
  

168
00:15:37,800 --> 00:15:42,160
Wyckoff saw the market as a 
fight between buyers and sellers. 

169
00:15:42,160 --> 00:15:48,840
Volume shows who's winning. High volume 
on up moves means buyers are strong. 

170
00:15:48,840 --> 00:15:53,360
High volume on down moves 
means sellers are in control.
  

171
00:15:53,360 --> 00:15:58,400
We talked before about Wyckoff's 
law of effort versus result. 

172
00:15:58,400 --> 00:16:04,560
This law says the effect of a price move should 
match the effort behind it. The effort is shown  

173
00:16:04,560 --> 00:16:09,300
by volume. The result is the price change.
 
Here's how it works: 

174
00:16:09,300 --> 00:16:14,560
• Big volume (the effort) should 
lead to big price moves (the result) 

175
00:16:14,560 --> 00:16:20,000
• Small volume should lead to small price moves.
• If there's a mismatch,  

176
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:24,920
it can signal a change coming
• High volume with little price change  

177
00:16:24,920 --> 00:16:30,760
often means accumulation or distribution
• Low volume with big price moves  

178
00:16:30,760 --> 00:16:34,600
usually isn't sustainable
• Rising prices with falling  

179
00:16:34,600 --> 00:16:41,120
volume can mean the uptrend is weakening
 
Volume helps confirm price action. It's  

180
00:16:41,120 --> 00:16:46,720
like a lie detector for price moves. Yes, 
price alone can sometimes lie, but price  

181
00:16:46,720 --> 00:16:53,520
and volume together usually tell the truth.
 
In accumulation, watch for high volume on down  

182
00:16:53,520 --> 00:16:59,680
days, that don't push prices much lower.
This can mean big players are buying,  

183
00:16:59,680 --> 00:17:04,960
soaking up the supply. It's a sign 
the downtrend might be ending. 

184
00:17:04,960 --> 00:17:11,720
In distribution, look for high volume on 
up days that don't push prices much higher. 

185
00:17:11,720 --> 00:17:18,680
This often means big players are selling into 
strength. It's a sign the uptrend might be ending. 

186
00:17:18,680 --> 00:17:24,120
During trends, volume should generally 
increase in the direction of the trend. 

187
00:17:24,120 --> 00:17:29,800
In an uptrend, volume should be 
higher on up days. In a downtrend,  

188
00:17:29,800 --> 00:17:34,160
volume should be higher on down days.
 
But it's not just about  

189
00:17:34,160 --> 00:17:39,400
whether volume is high or low.
The spread, the body of the price bar matters  

190
00:17:39,400 --> 00:17:47,480
too. Wyckoff and later traders like Tom Williams 
saw the relationship between volume and spread. 

191
00:17:47,480 --> 00:17:51,840
Here's what to look for:
Wide spread, high volume:  

192
00:17:51,840 --> 00:17:56,880
this means usually bullish
Wide spread, high volume:  

193
00:17:56,880 --> 00:18:01,880
this means usually bearish
Narrow spread, low volume:  

194
00:18:01,880 --> 00:18:07,160
often means consolidation
 
One common pattern is a climax.  

195
00:18:07,160 --> 00:18:13,720
This is a day with very high volume and a wide 
price range. It often marks the end of a move. 

196
00:18:13,720 --> 00:18:20,520
In a downtrend, it might be a selling climax, 
marking the end of the drop. In an uptrend,  

197
00:18:20,520 --> 00:18:24,760
it could be a buying climax, 
signaling the end of the rise.
  

198
00:18:24,760 --> 00:18:31,320
After a climax, watch for a test. This is 
when prices return to near the climax level,  

199
00:18:31,320 --> 00:18:36,080
but on lower volume. If the test 
holds, it can confirm the end of  

200
00:18:36,080 --> 00:18:42,920
the old trend and the start of a new one.
Volume can also help spot manipulation.  

201
00:18:42,920 --> 00:18:49,160
If you see a big price move on low volume, be 
suspicious. It might be a false move designed  

202
00:18:49,160 --> 00:18:57,280
to trick traders. Real, sustainable 
moves usually come with solid volume.
  

203
00:18:57,280 --> 00:19:03,720
In the Wyckoff method, volume isn't just 
about quantity. It's about quality too. 

204
00:19:03,720 --> 00:19:10,680
A day with steady buying is different from a 
day where all the volume comes in one big spike. 

205
00:19:10,680 --> 00:19:15,120
Learn to read the quality of 
volume, not just the quantity.
  

206
00:19:15,120 --> 00:19:20,080
One key skill is spotting 
divergences between price and volume. 

207
00:19:20,080 --> 00:19:27,160
If prices are making new highs but volume is 
dropping, it can mean the uptrend is weakening. 

208
00:19:27,160 --> 00:19:34,040
If prices are making new lows but volume is drying 
up, the downtrend might be running out of steam.
  

209
00:19:34,040 --> 00:19:39,760
Volume patterns can also hint at what's 
coming. For example, expanding volume as  

210
00:19:39,760 --> 00:19:46,520
prices move sideways often precedes a breakout.
The direction of the breakout isn't certain,  

211
00:19:46,520 --> 00:19:51,240
but the increase in volume suggests 
something big is cooking. 
  

212
00:19:51,240 --> 00:19:56,880
In accumulation, you might see a series 
of high-volume down days that fail to  

213
00:19:56,880 --> 00:20:03,800
push prices lower. This is often followed 
by an upward surge on even higher volume. 

214
00:20:03,800 --> 00:20:09,080
This pattern can signal the end of 
accumulation and the start of markup.
  

215
00:20:09,080 --> 00:20:12,680
In distribution, you might 
see a series of high-volume  

216
00:20:12,680 --> 00:20:19,400
up days that fail to push prices higher.
This is often followed by a downward plunge on  

217
00:20:19,400 --> 00:20:27,480
even higher volume. This pattern can signal the 
end of distribution and the start of markdown.
  

218
00:20:27,480 --> 00:20:33,080
Volume can also help with timing. In 
a strong trend, wait for a pullback  

219
00:20:33,080 --> 00:20:40,400
on lower volume before entering. This often 
provides a good entry point with lower risk.
  

220
00:20:40,400 --> 00:20:46,880
And one final point about this: volume often 
leads price. You might see volume patterns  

221
00:20:46,880 --> 00:20:54,617
change before price patterns do. This can give 
you an early warning of potential trend changes.

222
00:20:54,617 --> 00:20:56,280
Composite Man Concept
 
Wyckoff talked about the  

223
00:20:56,280 --> 00:21:02,720
"Composite Operator" in his books. This isn't 
one person. It's a way to think about all the  

224
00:21:02,720 --> 00:21:07,800
big players as if they were one.
These big players include banks,  

225
00:21:07,800 --> 00:21:11,840
hedge funds, and other pros.
And they often act in similar  

226
00:21:11,840 --> 00:21:19,040
ways. They're all trying to make money. And they 
have more info and power than regular traders.
  

227
00:21:19,040 --> 00:21:24,800
The Composite Man isn't real. It's a tool 
to help us understand the market. It's like  

228
00:21:24,800 --> 00:21:31,080
pretending the market has a mind of its own. 
And this mind is smart and sometimes tricky.
  

229
00:21:31,080 --> 00:21:35,120
Here's what the Composite Man does:
• He buys when prices are low. 

230
00:21:35,120 --> 00:21:39,600
• He sells when prices are high.
• He acts in its own interest. 

231
00:21:39,600 --> 00:21:44,600
• And he knows how to move prices.
 
The Composite Man doesn't control the  

232
00:21:44,600 --> 00:21:51,200
whole market. But it has a big impact. It 
can push prices up or down for a while. 

233
00:21:51,200 --> 00:21:57,640
The Composite Man concept helps explain why 
markets often move in ways that seem odd. 

234
00:21:57,640 --> 00:22:02,160
Why does price drop right before a 
good news release? The Composite Man  

235
00:22:02,160 --> 00:22:06,960
might be selling into the excitement.
Why does a market sometimes go up on  

236
00:22:06,960 --> 00:22:13,040
bad news? The Composite Man might have 
already sold. The bad news was expected.  

237
00:22:13,040 --> 00:22:18,920
Now it's buying again at lower prices.
 
Trading with the trend is key. If the  

238
00:22:18,920 --> 00:22:25,960
Composite Man is pushing price up, don't try to 
short. You'll probably lose. Go with the flow. 

239
00:22:25,960 --> 00:22:31,000
Again, always check volume. It's the 
footprint of the Composite Man. Big  

240
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:35,840
volume moves are often important.
 
The Composite Man links to other  

241
00:22:35,840 --> 00:22:41,040
Wyckoff ideas. Springs and upthrusts, for 
example, are often the work of the Composite  

242
00:22:41,040 --> 00:22:47,280
Man. We’ll talk about these in a minute.
This concept also explains why stop hunting  

243
00:22:47,280 --> 00:22:53,960
happens. The Composite Man knows where stops 
are likely to be. It can push price to hit those  

244
00:22:53,960 --> 00:23:00,280
stops. Then it trades against the stop orders.
You'll soon realize that see that many price moves  

245
00:23:00,280 --> 00:23:03,880
aren't random. They're often planned. 
 
 
Spring and Upthrust (Price Manipulation)

246
00:23:03,880 --> 00:23:08,760
The Spring and the Upthrust are 
key patterns in the Wyckoff method. 

247
00:23:08,760 --> 00:23:13,600
A Spring is a quick drop below 
support that bounces back fast. 

248
00:23:13,600 --> 00:23:18,640
An Upthrust is a quick push 
above resistance that fails fast. 

249
00:23:18,640 --> 00:23:25,600
Both are fake-outs that run stops outside 
support and resistance. Smart money concepts  

250
00:23:25,600 --> 00:23:33,520
named them liquidity sweeps or liquidity runs.
 
Why do they happen? Because big players often push  

251
00:23:33,520 --> 00:23:40,880
price past key levels to trigger stop losses. 
This lets them buy or sell at better prices.  

252
00:23:40,880 --> 00:23:47,840
It's like shaking a tree to make the fruit fall.
 
Let's look at Springs first. In a trading range,  

253
00:23:47,840 --> 00:23:54,560
price might dip below support. If it jumps back 
up fast, that's a Spring. It means there's strong  

254
00:23:54,560 --> 00:24:00,340
buying down there. It often leads to a move up.
 
Here's how to spot a Spring: 

255
00:24:00,340 --> 00:24:03,900
• Price is in a range
• It breaks below support 

256
00:24:03,900 --> 00:24:10,160
• It doesn't stay there long
• Then it jumps back above support fast
  

257
00:24:10,160 --> 00:24:14,200
Upthrusts are the opposite. 
Price pops above resistance,  

258
00:24:14,200 --> 00:24:21,520
but falls back quickly. It shows there's strong 
selling up there. It often leads to a move down.
  

259
00:24:21,520 --> 00:24:25,120
Here's how to spot an Upthrust:
• Price is in a range 

260
00:24:25,120 --> 00:24:29,300
• It breaks above resistance
• It doesn't stay there long 

261
00:24:29,300 --> 00:24:35,640
• Then it drops back below resistance fast
 
Both patterns show a fight between buyers  

262
00:24:35,640 --> 00:24:41,960
and sellers. In a Spring, sellers try 
to push price down, but buyers win. 

263
00:24:41,960 --> 00:24:47,120
In an Upthrust, buyers try to 
push price up, but sellers win. 

264
00:24:47,120 --> 00:24:52,080
For a Spring, the plan is to buy 
when price jumps back above support 

265
00:24:52,080 --> 00:24:57,120
For an Upthrust, you sell when 
price drops back below resistance
  

266
00:24:57,120 --> 00:25:01,640
But it's not always that easy. You 
need to look at the bigger picture too. 

267
00:25:01,640 --> 00:25:08,160
For Springs, check if the overall trend is 
up. A Spring in an uptrend is stronger than  

268
00:25:08,160 --> 00:25:13,680
one in a downtrend. Look for signs 
of accumulation before the Spring. 

269
00:25:13,680 --> 00:25:19,440
This makes the pattern more likely to work .
 
For Upthrusts, check if the overall trend  

270
00:25:19,440 --> 00:25:25,080
is down. An Upthrust in a downtrend 
is stronger than one in an uptrend. 

271
00:25:25,080 --> 00:25:28,600
Look for signs of distribution 
before the Upthrust.  

272
00:25:28,600 --> 00:25:35,160
This makes the pattern more likely to work .
 
Volume is key in these patterns. In a Spring,  

273
00:25:35,160 --> 00:25:40,680
you want to see high volume on the drop 
and even higher volume on the bounce. 

274
00:25:40,680 --> 00:25:42,920
This shows strong buying. 
  

275
00:25:42,920 --> 00:25:47,360
In an Upthrust, you want high 
volume on the push up and even  

276
00:25:47,360 --> 00:25:55,160
higher on the drop. This shows strong selling .
Some traders do well without focusing on volume.  

277
00:25:55,160 --> 00:26:01,520
The price action itself can be enough.
 
The context matters a lot. A Spring or  

278
00:26:01,520 --> 00:26:06,120
Upthrust at the end of a long trend is 
more powerful than one in the middle  

279
00:26:06,120 --> 00:26:14,000
of a range. It might signal a big trend change.
 
One trick is to look for smaller ranges near the  

280
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:21,240
edge of bigger ranges. These often lead to good 
breakouts. You might see Springs or Upthrusts  

281
00:26:21,240 --> 00:26:28,400
in these smaller ranges before a big move.
 
Sometimes, you won't see a Spring or Upthrust  

282
00:26:28,400 --> 00:26:34,800
at all. This is called a structural failure. 
It happens when price fails to reach one side  

283
00:26:34,800 --> 00:26:40,880
of a range and then breaks out the other 
way. This can be a strong signal too.
  

284
00:26:40,880 --> 00:26:46,040
One way to practice is to look for these 
patterns after the fact. Go through old  

285
00:26:46,040 --> 00:26:52,280
charts. Mark the Springs and Upthrusts.
See what happened after. This trains your  

286
00:26:52,280 --> 00:26:55,560
eye to spot them in real-time.
 
 
Advanced Wyckoff Concepts

287
00:26:55,560 --> 00:26:59,280
Now let's dive into some 
advanced Wyckoff concepts. 

288
00:26:59,280 --> 00:27:04,640
One advanced concept is the "creek".
This is a small, tight trading range  

289
00:27:04,640 --> 00:27:08,400
that forms after a big move.
It's like a pause in the  

290
00:27:08,400 --> 00:27:13,880
action. But it's not random.
 
It often shows up at key points in trends. 

291
00:27:13,880 --> 00:27:17,760
Creeks can be hard to spot if 
you're not looking for them. 

292
00:27:17,760 --> 00:27:23,320
They might look like normal price action. 
But they can signal big moves ahead.
  

293
00:27:23,320 --> 00:27:27,520
Here's how to use creeks:
• Look for them after strong trends 

294
00:27:27,520 --> 00:27:34,200
• Check if volume dries up in the creek
• Watch for a strong move out of the creek 

295
00:27:34,200 --> 00:27:38,800
If you see these things, it might be 
a good trade setup. The move out of  

296
00:27:38,800 --> 00:27:44,680
the creek often starts a new trend.
 
Another advanced concept is the idea  

297
00:27:44,680 --> 00:27:51,480
of "tests". These are like mini-versions of 
springs and upthrusts. They happen all the time,  

298
00:27:51,480 --> 00:27:56,240
not just at major turning points.
A test is when price moves back to  

299
00:27:56,240 --> 00:28:03,440
a previous support or resistance level. It's 
checking if that level still holds. If it does,  

300
00:28:03,440 --> 00:28:08,200
it can be a good entry point for a trade.
 
Tests are powerful because they show  

301
00:28:08,200 --> 00:28:13,120
real supply and demand in action.
They're not just lines on a chart. They  

302
00:28:13,120 --> 00:28:20,680
show where real buying and selling is happening.
Here's a pro tip: look for tests that fail. If  

303
00:28:20,680 --> 00:28:26,840
price tests a level and breaks through, that 
can signal a big move. It means the previous  

304
00:28:26,840 --> 00:28:33,840
support or resistance isn't working anymore.
 
Another advanced idea is "absorption". This  

305
00:28:33,840 --> 00:28:39,920
is when big players buy or sell without 
moving price much. It's hard to spot,  

306
00:28:39,920 --> 00:28:43,640
but it's a powerful signal.
Absorption often shows up as  

307
00:28:43,640 --> 00:28:49,160
high volume but little price movement. 
It might look boring on a chart. But  

308
00:28:49,160 --> 00:28:55,760
it can signal that a big move is coming.
 
Wyckoff traders always think about context.  

309
00:28:55,760 --> 00:29:01,880
They don't just look at patterns. They think about 
where those patterns fit in the bigger picture. 

310
00:29:01,880 --> 00:29:07,440
For example, a spring in an uptrend is 
different from a spring in a downtrend.  

311
00:29:07,440 --> 00:29:13,840
A test of support after a long uptrend is 
different from a test early in a trend.
  

312
00:29:13,840 --> 00:29:19,400
Another advanced idea is "swing analysis". 
This is about measuring the strength of  

313
00:29:19,400 --> 00:29:25,600
moves up and down. It can show you if 
a trend is gaining or losing strength. 

314
00:29:25,600 --> 00:29:31,520
In an uptrend, you want to see higher 
highs and higher lows. But how much higher? 

315
00:29:31,520 --> 00:29:36,880
Swing analysis helps you measure this. 
If the swings are getting weaker,  

316
00:29:36,880 --> 00:29:42,600
it might signal a trend change coming.
 
Another advanced idea is "the fractal  

317
00:29:42,600 --> 00:29:49,160
analysis". This is about understanding that 
Wyckoff patterns show up on all timeframes. 

318
00:29:49,160 --> 00:29:55,280
A spring on a 5-minute chart works the 
same way as one on a monthly chart. 

319
00:29:55,280 --> 00:29:59,200
Understanding fractals can help 
you trade multiple timeframes. 

320
00:29:59,200 --> 00:30:04,840
You might use a bigger timeframe for 
direction, and a smaller one for entries. 

321
00:30:04,840 --> 00:30:20,480
Now, if you liked what you saw, we have plenty 
more interesting trading guides for you!

